'''Andrew Bernard "Barney" Gilligan''' (January 3, 1856{{ndash}} April 1, 1934) was a [[professional baseball]] player whose career spanned 12 seasons, 11 of which were spent with the [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) [[Brooklyn Atlantics]] (1875), [[Cleveland Blues (NL)|Cleveland Blues]] (1879<U+2013>1880), [[Providence Grays]] (1881<U+2013>1885), [[Washington Nationals (1886-89)|Washington Nationals]] (1886<U+2013>1887), and [[Detroit Wolverines]] (1888). Gilligan, who predominately played as a [[catcher]], also played as an [[outfielder]] and a [[shortstop]]. Over his career, Gilligan compiled a career [[batting average]] of .207 with 217 [[run (baseball)|runs scored]], 388 [[hit (baseball)|hits]], 68 [[Double (baseball)|doubles]], 23 [[triple (baseball)|triples]], three [[home run]]s, and 167 [[runs batted in]] (RBI) in 523 [[games played]]. Although the majority of his career was spent in the major leagues, Burns also played in [[minor league baseball]]. He made his MLB debut at the age of 19 and was listed as standing {{convert|5|ft|6|in|cm}} and weighing {{convert|130|lb|kg}}.<ref name="SABR">{{cite web|last=McKenna|first=Brian|title=Barney Gilligan|url=http://bioproj.sabr.org/bioproj.cfm?a=v&v=l&bid=3583&pid=5137|work=The Society for American Baseball Research Biography Project|publisher=[[The Society for American Baseball Research]]|accessdate=August 11, 2011}}</ref>

==Early life==
Andrew Bernard Gilligan was born in  [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]] on January 3, 1856.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gammons|first=Peter|title=The 2006 ESPN Baseball Encyclopedia|editor=Pete Palmer, Gary Gillette, Stuart Shea|publisher=Sterling|year=2006|page=252|isbn=1402736258|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=eUe37F9gN00C}}</ref> He was the sixth child of seven born to Patrick Gilligan, a laborer, and Sarah Gilligan. Both Patrick and Sarah had immigrated to the United States from [[Northern Ireland]].<ref name="SABR" />

==Professional career==
Gilligan began his professional career playing [[right field]] in 1874 for the New York Flyaways, an amateur baseball club.<ref name="SABR" /> Gilligan continued to play for the Flyaways in 1875 until Gilligan and a former Flyaway, [[Bill Rexter]], joined the Brooklyn Atlantics for their final two games of the season.<ref name="SABR" /> He continued his professional baseball career in 1876 and 1877. In 1878, Gilligan played for various minor-league clubs such as the Somerville Unions of [[Somerville, Massachusetts]], and the Charlestown Alerts of [[Charlestown, Boston|Charlestown, Massachusetts]].<ref name="SABR" />

In his first full MLB season, Gilligan played for the Cleveland Blues. After his first game with the Blues, the ''[[Cleveland Leader]]'' stated "Gilligan caught exceedingly well taking some fine pickups."<ref name="SABR" /> Over 52 games played, Gilligan batted a career-low .171 with 11 RBI and six doubles.<ref name="ESPN">{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/player/stats/_/id/22068/barney-gilligan|title=Barney Gilligan Stats|work=ESPN|accessdate=September 8, 2011}}</ref> Defensively, he played 27 games as catcher and 23 as an outfielder. Next season, Gilligan continued to play for the Blues, again serving as backup catcher to [[Doc Kennedy]]<ref name="SABR" /> before leaving the team at the end of the season to sign with the Providence Grays. With the Grays, he served again as a backup catcher before the starter ([[Emil Gross]]) became injured;<ref name="SABR" /> on the season, Gilligan batted .219 with 20 RBI. Next year, in 1882, Gilligan became the starting catcher for the Grays; his backup, [[Sandy Nava]], was the first Mexican-American baseball player.<ref name="SABR" /> When the season was over, the Grays finished 52<U+2013>32, second in the [[National League]] (NL), under manager [[Harry Wright]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/PRO/1882.shtml|title=1882 Providence Grays Batting, Pitching, & Fielding Statistics|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=September 9, 2011}}</ref>
[[File:1884grays.jpg|thumb|right|The 1884 World Series champion Grays|alt=A black-and-white photo of the 1884 Providence Grays]]
By 1883, Gilligan had become the Grays starting catcher. Despite breaking his finger and missing two weeks in May, Gilligan led the National League in [[Assist (baseball)|assists]] as a catcher,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/NL/1883-fielding-leaders.shtml|title=1883 National League Fielding Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=September 9, 2011}}</ref> while his team finished third in the NL. He continued his tenure with the Grays the following season. Gilligan played in a career-high 82 games, while also recording career highs in RBI (38), [[strikeout]]s (41), and [[on-base percentage]] (.325)<ref name="ESPN" /> and leading MLB in defensive games as a catcher (81).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/MLB/1884-fielding-leaders.shtml|title=1884 Major League Baseball Fielding Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=September 9, 2011}}</ref> After finishing at the top of the NL, the Grays played in the [[1884 World Series]] against the [[New York Metropolitans]] of the [[American Association]]. Gilligan went 4<U+2013>for<U+2013>9 over the three-game series, with the Grays defeating the Metropolitans three games to none.<ref name="SABR" />

After spending the 1885 season with the Grays, and tying [[Andy Cusick]] for the MLB lead in [[error (baseball)|errors]] committed as a catcher,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/MLB/1885-fielding-leaders.shtml|title=1885 Major League Baseball Fielding Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=September 9, 2011}}</ref> the Grays management sold out in November of that year.<ref name="SABR" /> The NL bought the Grays for [[USD|$]]6,000, while Gilligan was assigned to the Washington Nationals. He served as captain of the team for the 1886 season, catching 71 games and batting .190. Before the 1887 season, he established a restaurant in the [[District of Columbia]].<ref name="SABR" />

{{Quote box
 |quote  = "[Cliff] [[Cliff Carroll|Carroll]] was released by Washington last week. He and Barney Gilligan are both out in the cold; yet, both are good ballplayers. Fooling with [whiskey] has cost them dearly."
 |source = An 1887 issue of the ''[[Oshkosh Northwestern|Oshkosh Daily Northwestern]]''<ref name="SABR" />
 |width  = 40%
 |align  = right
 |style=clear:none;max-width:50%
}}

In 1887, Gilligan was fined $25 for [[binge drinking]] and missing a game for the Nationals.<ref name="SABR" /> The next season, Gilligan was released by the team. In his final MLB season, Gilligan signed with the Detroit Wolverines. He played in one game for the team, going 1<U+2013>for<U+2013>5 with a run and a strikeout.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/DTN/1888.shtml|title=1888 Detroit Wolverines Batting, Pitching, & Fielding Statistics|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=September 9, 2011}}</ref> Later that year, Gilligan signed with the [[Lynn Shoemakers]], appearing in 11 games before joining the [[Manchester Maroons]] for three games. For the next three years, Gilligan continued to play minor league baseball.<ref name="SABR" />

His career MLB batting average (.207) is tied with [[John Henry (catcher)|John Henry]] for the seventh lowest all-time among batters with at least 1,000 [[at bat]]s.<ref>{{cite book|title=The SABR baseball list & record book: baseball's most fascinating records and unusual statistics|page=20|year=2007|publisher=Simon and Schuster|last=Spatz|first=Lyle|coauthor=Society for American Baseball Research|isbn=978-1-4165-3245-3}}</ref>

==After baseball==
After retiring from baseball, Gilligan lived in [[Lynn, Massachusetts]], with his wife, Sara. He worked as a garbage collector before dying of [[erysipelas]] on April 1, 1934. Gilligan was intered at [[Pine Grove Cemetery (Lynn, Massachusetts)|Pine Grove Cemetery]] in Lynn.<ref name="SABR" />

